The Vice President of the United States, Joe Biden, met with Slovene Prime Minister Borut Pahor to discuss their shared agenda of promoting peace, stability, and prosperity in Europe and beyond. They discussed ways to integrate Slovenia's neighbors into Euro-Atlantic structures, particularly Croatia's European Union candidacy. The leaders also talked about trade and investment opportunities, with the Vice President expressing appreciation for the Prime Minister's efforts to improve the investment climate in Slovenia. President Barack Obama also joined part of the meeting to acknowledge the strong bilateral relationship between the United States and Slovenia, and to thank Slovenia for its support in Afghanistan and contributions to NATO's International Security Assistance Force (ISAF). They also reviewed the current situation in Southeastern Europe.